# **Planning**

I have taken Dr. Lu’s advice to continue thinking about the purpose and context of my project.  
I feel that a common thread in glitching is this relationship between input and output. Glitches occur as a result of non-standard input causing processing issues that cause an unpredictable output. So, in my project, I plan to explore this relationship of input and output. However, it will need to be extremely simple, because creating a full-blown file format and letting the player write their own files is way out of scale and typing is annoying in VR. 

I’m still workshopping it, but I plan on having “fake” file types that can be put into any reader device. There will be distinct readers for things like videos, images, audio, or 3D models, but you can but any file type in them to cause unpredictable output.

With control panels, I think it will be like tuning an instrument where you tweak settings to affect the output systematically.

With ephemerality, I could have the file objects slowly decay and “lose data” which leads to increasingly corrupted inputs. However, I’m afraid this will remove the user from engaging in glitch as they aren’t doing the corrupting. I still need to think about this.

I played around with the idea of having the player physically connect in-game devices with wires. For example, the player would have to plug in a cable from a video playing device into a TV so that the TV could output what was being played. This mechanic would be about connectivity and links and networks, but I’m afraid that would be too different from the relationship of input/output and would blow the scale way up. I will shelve the idea for now, but if I can make significant progress in building the project, I will revisit the idea.

## **Fake Gramaphone**

There can be an audio output device that looks like a gramophone, and you can replace the vinyl that is inside with vinyls from some box. However, changing the disc won’t replace the audio. To do that, you need to go to the cabinet below the gramophone and replace the file that the device is reading. I think this does something interesting with interfaces and the gap between what we think is happening and what actually happens.
